{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17514419","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17514419"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:22:14+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:22:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12315"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12315","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12315"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.52,0.14,0.15,0.18,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4836"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109045"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4836","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4836"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question","status":"accepted","createdAt":"2022-12-10T23:43:14+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-16T15:41:41+09:30","updatedAction":"commented","acceptedAt":"2024-04-23T10:20:37+09:30","editorNotifiedAt":null,"feedbackAt":"2025-09-22 18:19:34"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12315"}},"updatedBy":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"9"}},"author":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"6633"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91411"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1149"},{"type":"tags","id":"2203"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7786"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11516"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26462"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40712"}]},"lastContribution":{"data":null},"lastRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91411"}},"lastActivity":{"data":null},"lastFeedback":{"data":null}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109045","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/109045"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old man presents to his general practitioner, concerned about a swelling in the right side of his scrotum when he recently noticed while showering. He describes the sensation as feeling like \u0022a third testis\u0022. He denies experiencing any associated symptoms such as pain, discomfort, or changes in urinary habits and is otherwise in good health.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, a lax, 3 cm cystic swelling can be felt immediately above the upper pole of the right testis, which itself feels normal. The swelling does not elicit tenderness upon palpation and there is some transillumination under light examination. The rest of the scrotal examination is normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Spermatocele","Hydrocele","Varicocele","Testicular tumour","Torsion of the testicular appendix"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EFrom the description of the lesion and its position immediately above the testis, this swelling is either an epididymal cyst or a spermatocele. As it does not transilluminate, it is more likely to be a \u003Cstrong\u003Espermatocele\u003C/strong\u003E. Spermatoceles are cystic swellings, often described as feeling like a \u0022third testis,\u0022 located above the testis. They contain varying concentrations of sperm and typically appear painless and non-tender. The fact that this swelling does not transilluminate well is also characteristic of a spermatocele, where a high concentration of sperm will inhibit transillumination. Spermatoceles are usually asymptomatic, tend to occur in older men and may be discovered incidentally by the patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ehydrocele\u003C/strong\u003E is a collection of peritoneal fluid between the parietal and visceral layers of the tunica vaginalis enveloping the testicle. It can present as a painless, fluctuant swelling in the scrotum. Hydroceles can transilluminate well. However, the description of a lax, cystic swelling on top of the testis suggests a more localised cystic structure, making hydrocele less likely in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Evaricocele\u003C/strong\u003E is an abnormal dilatation of the pampiniform venous plexus\u00a0within the spermatic cord. They present as a lump, often described as feeling like a \u201cbag of worms\u201d or with a \u201cdragging sensation\u201d and may disappear on lying flat. While varicoceles can cause swelling and discomfort, they typically occur along the spermatic cord and are not typically described as a third testis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETesticular tumours\u003C/strong\u003E can present as painless testicular masses. Examination may reveal a firm irregular mass, which does not transilluminate. They are less likely in this case given the absence of tenderness and the cystic nature of the swelling described. Additionally, testicular tumours are not usually described as feeling like a third testis. This patient is in the wrong age group for a testicular neoplasm, most occurring in adolescents or young adults.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETorsion of the testicular appendix \u003C/strong\u003Eusually presents with acute onset pain in the scrotum, often described as severe and sudden. It typically occurs in younger boys and adolescents. Unlike the described case, torsion of the testicular appendix is characterised by pain, whereas the patient in this scenario denies experiencing any associated symptoms such as pain or discomfort. Additionally, the physical examination findings of a cystic swelling on top of the right testis are not consistent with torsion of the testicular appendix, which typically presents with \u0022blue dot sign\u0022 It refers to a bluish or violaceous discoloration seen through the scrotal skin, typically at the upper pole of the affected testicle. This discoloration occurs due to congestion or ischaemia of the appendix testis following torsion, leading to venous engorgement and visible vascular changes on the skin.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Spermatoceles are cystic swellings, often described as feeling like a \u0022third testis,\u0022 located immediately above the testis."],"references":["Wampler SM, Lanes M.  Common Scrotal and Testicular Problems. Prim Care Clin Office Pract 2010: 37:613\u201326"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91411"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12315"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91411","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/91411"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-16T15:41:34+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-16T15:42:57+09:30","number":7,"notes":"","plagiarismCheckedAt":"2025-07-16T15:41:40+09:30","plagiarismScore":11.6,"plagiarismReportUrl":"https://emedici-copyleaks.syd1.digitaloceanspaces.com/plagiarism-report-4836-7.pdf?X-Amz-Content-Sha256=UNSIGNED-PAYLOAD\u0026X-Amz-Algorithm=AWS4-HMAC-SHA256\u0026X-Amz-Credential=DO00QAKVE68N83EBLT2J%2F20250929%2Fsyd1%2Fs3%2Faws4_request\u0026X-Amz-Date=20250929T035216Z\u0026X-Amz-SignedHeaders=host\u0026X-Amz-Expires=601200\u0026X-Amz-Signature=d59d004810ce6dbe88591b0b2963c160e46cf0a23563c7b57c42b594652f136c"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4836"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109045"}},"author":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"9"}},"generation":{"data":null}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"creat